<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: OLYMPICS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 John Krimsky Jr., who has helped pad America's Olympic pockets by negotiating 
multimillion-dollar sponsorship deals, was chosen interim executive director of 
the U.S. Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
 Krimsky, deputy secretary general and chief fund-raiser who has been with the 
USOC since 1986, was picked for the interim post in a conference call of the 
committee's executive board. 
</P>
<P>
 Starting Oct. 1, he takes over for Harvey Schiller, who is leaving the USOC's 
top operating post to become president of Turner Sports in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
 A panel to find a permanent successor for Schiller will be appointed by Sept. 
16, but there is no deadline for filling the job, according to USOC President 
LeRoy Walker. 
</P>
<P>
 Potential candidates mentioned as successor to Schiller include Jack Kelly, 
president of the Goodwill Games; Donna Lopiano, executive director of the 
Women's Sports Foundation; Mike Jacki, president of U.S. Skiing; Jerry Lace, 
executive director of the U.S. Figure Skating Association; and Steve Hatchell, 
commissioner of the Southwest Conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
