<P>
GLENDALE / BURBANK FOCUS: GLENDALE; CARDINAL MAHONY TO DEDICATE SERVICE SITE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Cardinal Roger Mahony will preside over dedication and reopening ceremonies 
for the Glendale Community Center, formerly known as the Catholic Youth 
Organization building, at 10 a.m. Aug. 29. 
</P>
<P>
 The CYO has been closed for more than two years.The organization's dilapidated 
structure at 4322 San Fernando Road was torn down and its 6,200-square-foot 
replacement was built with $622,000 in federal Housing and Urban Development 
funds allocated by the city. 
</P>
<P>
 A food pantry is already open at the new center. Over the next few months, the 
center will begin offering many other services, including earthquake 
assistance, family counseling, senior issues advocacy, Alcoholics Anonymous and 
Al-Anon meetings, and immigration processing. The center will also offer youth 
activities as well as English as a second language classes. 
</P>
<P>
 "I live in this community, and I see that there is a real need for our 
programs," said Carlos Reyes, former director of the CYO and a staff member at 
the new center. "There was a real void left when the center closed." 
</P>
<P>
 The food pantry, operated on the site by Loaves and Fishes Catholic Charities, 
provides needy families with groceries on a periodic basis and homeless singles 
with free sack lunches. Loaves and Fishes also provides counseling for the 
homeless or those at risk of becoming homeless. STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</TEXT>
